{{Infobox civilian attack | title = Crime of Gádor | image = Cortijo de San Patricio.jpg | caption = Cortijo de San Patricio, where the murder occurred | map = LocationGádor.png | map_caption = Location of Gádor | coordinates = {{Coord|36|56|28|N|2|28|36|W|display=title}} | date = {{start date|1910|06|28}} | type = [[Kidnapping]] | victims = Bernardo Gonzalez Parra | perpetrators = {{plainlist| * Agustina Rodríguez * Francisco Ortega ''el Moruno'' * José Hernández * Julio "El Tonto" Hernández * [[Francisco Leona]] }} | assailants = | susperps = | weapons = [[Knife]] and [[stone]] | verdict = Guilty }}
The '''crime of Gádor''' was the name given to the kidnapping and subsequent murder of a seven-year-old boy by [[Francisco Leona]] in [[Gádor]], [[Almería]]. The purpose of the crime was to use the child's blood and body fat as a folk cure for a wealthy patron's tuberculosis.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jiménez Elizari |first=Iker |author-link=Iker Jiménez Elizari |title=El paraíso maldito |url=https://books.google.es/books?id=JiRSQ6HnVhQC&pg=PA199 |chapter=Jáncanas y brujas: Señoras de la magia |chapter-url=https://books.google.es/books?id=JiRSQ6HnVhQC&pg=PA185 |publisher=EDAF |date=April 6, 2006 |page=199 |isbn=9788441417724}}</ref>
== Background == [[File:Francisco Leona 02.jpg|thumb|Francisco Leona {{circa|1910}}]] At the time, it was believed that drinking the [[human blood|blood]] of a human child and using their body fat as [[cataplasm]] was a remedy for [[tuberculosis]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Costa |first=Pedro |title=La vampira del carrer Ponent |url=https://elpais.com/diario/2006/01/01/eps/1136100421_850215.html |date=January 1, 2006 |access-date=March 27, 2018 |newspaper=[[El País]] |language=es |publisher=Ediciones El País, S.L. |editor-last=Caño |editor-first=Antonio |issn=0213-4608}}</ref>
Francisco Ortega ''El Moruno'' (''The Moor'') had recently been diagnosed with [[tuberculosis]] and was desperately seeking a cure.<ref name=SanzyDíaz>{{cite journal |last=Sanz y Díaz |first=José |year=1984 |title=Etnografía negra. El crimen que dio lugar a la leyenda de "El Sacamantecas" |url=http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/obra/etnografia-negra-el-crimen-que-dio-lugar-a-la-leyenda-de-el-sacamantecas/ |pages=171–174 |magazine=Revista de Folklore |issue=47 |volume=4b |access-date=March 27, 2018 |location=Valladolid}}</ref> He visited the local [[curandera]] Agustina Rodriguez, who in turn sent for the barber and healer [[Francisco Leona]].<ref name=SanzyDíaz/> Leona, who also had a criminal record, agreed to cure Ortega in exchange for 3000 [[Spanish real|real]]es.<ref name=SanzyDíaz/>
Leona and Julio ''El Tonto'' (''The Fool'') Hernández, a son of Agustina the healer, offered to find a child. On the evening of June 27, 1910, Francisco Leona [[child abduction|kidnapped]] Bernardo Gonzalez Parra, a seven year old from [[Rioja, Almería|Rioja]], drugged him with [[chloroform]] and put him in a sack.{{sfn|Fernández Juárez|2008|p=22}}
== Murder == A brother of Julio "Tonto" Hernández, Joseph Hernández, was to advise the client Ortega, leaving his wife Elena to make dinner.
Little Bernardo's murder was as follows: after he was removed from the sack, dazed, Bernardo was stabbed in the [[heart]] by Leona, and Ortega mixed his blood with sugar and drank it.{{sfn|Fernández Juárez|2008|p=22}} After that they took the boy to a place known as [[Las Pocicas]] where Leona killed him, crushing his skull with a rock. Then he extracted [[human fat|fat]] and [[mesentery]] to make a compress to apply to Ortega's chest.
To finish the ritual, Bernardo's body was concealed in a crevice, unburied but covered with herbs and stones, located in Las Pocicas.
When distributing the actual 3000 Ortega paid him for his services, the healer Leona tried and failed to trick his accomplice ''Tonto'' Hernández. Realizing Leona's intentions, Hernández told the Civil Guard who had seen the body of a child while he was chasing [[partridge]]s.
== Judicial and police intervention == [[File:CottageAlm 01.jpg|thumb|Cortijo de San Patricio at present]] When law enforcement officers arrived, the people of Gádor turned Leona over to them, as he was known for his illegal and occult practices.{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=16}} During court proceedings, Leona indicted ''el Tonto'' Hernández in his testimony, who in turn did the same to Leona.{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=16}} Finally, after multiple excuses, both confessed to the crime.{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=17}}
Most of the perpetrators were [[executed by hanging]].{{sfn|Fernández Juárez|2008|p=22}} Leona was sentenced to death by [[garrote vil|garrote]], but died in prison.{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=18}} The client, Ortega, and Agustina, the [[curandera]], were both sentenced to [[death penalty|death]].{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=18}} Joseph Hernández, was sentenced to 17 years in prison while his wife, Elena, was acquitted. Julio ''el Tonto'' was sentenced to death too, but received a pardon on [[criminally insane|grounds of insanity]] following a psychiatric report.{{sfn|García Bautista|2015|p=18}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturandalucia.com/ALMERÍA/El_crimen_de_Gador_Almeria.htm |last=Soler Cervantes |first=Milagros |title=El crimen de Gádor (Almería) |access-date=February 22, 2015 |work=Cultura en Andalucía |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Gómez Aracil |first=Miguel |title=Vampiros: Mito y realidad de los no muertos |url=https://books.google.es/books?id=8cW9cFF06VYC&pg=PA139 |publisher=EDAF |date=November 25, 2009 |page=139 |isbn=9788441421622}}</ref>
== Aftermath == This crime gave rise to the term [[Hombre del saco]] and [[Sacamantecas]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Ayala Sörense |first=Federico |title=El verdadero "Hombre del Saco" |url=http://www.abc.es/abcfoto/revelado/20140925/abci-crimen-hombre-saco-201409242057.html |editor-last=Expósiot |editor-first=Ángel |date=September 25, 2014 |access-date=March 27, 2018 |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |language=es |publisher=Diario ABC, S.L.}}</ref> because the kidnapers used a [[gunny sack]] to carry the children.{{sfn|Fernández Juárez|2008|p=61}} It was defined as "medical crime", inspired by the believes of the virtue of the therapy of the [[human blood]] and the child's ''[[Body fat|manteca]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Caro Baroja |first=Julio |title=De etnología andaluza |url=https://books.google.es/books?id=TN8bCvlEK4UC |chapter=Notas de viajes por Andalucía |editor-last=Carreira |editor-first=Antonio |page=179 |publisher=[[Diputación Provincial de Málaga]]}}</ref>
A TV episode named ''El sacamantecas'' was released in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtve.es/alacarta/videos/pagina-de-sucesos/355536-i10513-sacamantecas-20141201143111306-web/2884290/ |title=Página de sucesos - El sacamantecas |date=10 January 1986 |access-date=10 August 2018 |work=[[Radio Televisión Española]] |language=es}}</ref>
