{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name = James Bumphrey | image = | caption = | fullname = James Bumphrey<ref name=Matthews76/> | birth_date = 4 May 1884<ref name="navy"/> | birth_place = [[Morpeth, Northumberland]], England | death_date = 1946 (age 61)<ref>England & Wales, Civil Registration Death Index, 1916-2007</ref> | death_place = Northumberland, England | height = {{height|ft=5|in=8}} | position = [[Wing half]] | youthyears1 = – | youthclubs1 = | years1 = – | clubs1 = Ashington Alliance | years2 = 1908–1915 | clubs2 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] | caps2 = 136 | goals2 = 7 | years3 = 1915–19?? | clubs3 = [[Durham City A.F.C.|Durham City]] }}
'''James Bumphrey''' (4 May 1884 – after 1919) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played 136 games and scored 7 goals in [[the Football League]] for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]].<ref name=Matthews76>{{cite book |first=Tony |last=Matthews |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9 |page=76}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData (Tony Brown) |location=Nottingham |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref>
Bumphrey was born in [[Morpeth, Northumberland]], and played for Ashington Alliance before joining Birmingham in August 1908. A heavily built man, he was a strong tackler, though "a little wild", and headed the ball well despite being only {{height|ft=5|in=8}} tall.<ref name=Matthews76/> He made his debut in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] on 31 December 1908, playing at [[inside forward|inside left]] in a 1–1 draw away to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>Matthews, p.&nbsp;155.</ref> For the next couple of seasons he played sporadically, always in the forward line, until becoming a regular in the side at [[wing half]].<ref>Matthews, pp.&nbsp;155–58.</ref> He made 143 appearances in all competitions for Birmingham in seven years, before moving back to his native north-east when the Football League suspended during the [[First World War]].<ref name=Matthews76/>
During the First World War, he served in the [[Royal Navy]] from 1917–19, serving aboard {{HMS|Princess Royal|1911|6}}.<ref name="navy">James Bumphrey; Birth Date: 4 May 1884; Birth Place: Morpeth Northumberland; ''UK, Royal Navy Registers of Seamen's Services, 1848-1939''</ref>
