[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Sir Joseph Sydney Yorke''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] (6 June 1768 – 5 May 1831) was an officer of the [[Royal Navy]]. As a junior officer he saw action at the [[Battle of the Saintes]] in April 1782 during the [[American Revolutionary War]]. He commanded {{HMS|Stag|1794|6}} at the [[Action of 22 August 1795|defeat of the Dutch fleet]] in August 1795 during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and went on to be [[First Sea Lord|First Naval Lord]] during the closing stages of the [[Napoleonic Wars]].

==Family and early life==
Yorke was born in [[Berkhamsted|Great Berkhampstead]], Hertfordshire, on 6 June 1768, the second son, by his second marriage, of the politician [[Charles Yorke]].<ref name="United Service">{{cite book |last= |title=United Service Magazine |pages=215–217}}</ref> He joined the navy at the age of 11, becoming a [[midshipman]] aboard {{HMS|Duke|1777|6}}, then under the command of [[Sir Charles Douglas, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Douglas]], on 15 February 1780. He followed Douglas to his next command, {{HMS|Formidable|1777|6}}, which flew the flag of Admiral [[George Brydges Rodney, 1st Baron Rodney|George Rodney]].<ref name="United Service"/>  Yorke was then present at Rodney's victory over [[François Joseph Paul de Grasse]] at the [[Battle of the Saintes]] from 9 April to 12 April 1782. The end of the American Revolutionary War led to the ''Formidable'' returning to Britain to be paid off. Yorke remained in employment however, transferring with Douglas to {{HMS|Assistance|1747|6}}, and then moving to {{HMS|Salisbury|1769|6}}, under the command of Sir [[Erasmus Gower]], filling the post of [[master's mate]].  Yorke spent three years in total serving on the [[Newfoundland Station]].<ref name="United Service"/>

==Promotions==
Yorke was promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 16 June 1789, and moved aboard the 50-gun {{HMS|Adamant|1780|6}} to serve under Admiral [[Sir Richard Hughes, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Hughes]].<ref name="United Service"/> He later served as lieutenant aboard {{HMS|Thisbe|1783|6}} and {{HMS|Victory}} and in February 1791 he was appointed master and commander of the [[sloop-of-war|sloop]] {{HMS|Rattlesnake|1791|6}}. He remained aboard her, carrying out cruises into the [[English Channel]] until the outbreak of [[French Revolutionary Wars|war]] with France in 1793. He was promoted to [[Post-Captain]] on 4 February 1793 and given command of the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Circe|1785|6}}, then part of a squadron under Admiral [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Richard Howe]]. He patrolled off the French port of [[Brest, France|Brest]], and captured the [[corvette]] ''L'Espiegle''.<ref name="United Service"/>

[[File:Defeat of the Dutch Fleet off Egero, 22 August 1795.jpg|thumb|left|''Defeat of the Dutch Fleet off Egerö, 22 August 1795'', [[Nicholas Pocock]], 1795; Yorke took part in the action]]
Yorke moved to {{HMS|Stag|1794|6}} in July 1794, and continued to serve in the Channel, occasionally ranging into the [[North Sea]]. On 22 August 1795 the ''Stag'' and a small British squadron chased two large ships and a [[cutter (ship)|cutter]], eventually bringing the sternmost one to battle. [[Action of 22 August 1795|An hour-long fight]] ensued, after which the enemy, subsequently found to be the [[Batavian Republic|Batavian]] frigate ''Alliance'', was forced to surrender.<ref name="United Service"/> Yorke moved to command the newly built {{HMS|Jason|1800|6}} in March 1800, and by 1801 was in command of the 74-gun [[third rate]] {{HMS|Canada|1765|6}}. He commanded her until the [[Treaty of Amiens]] in 1802 brought a period of temporary peace.<ref name="United Service"/> On the resumption of the war in 1803 Yorke was appointed to the 98-gun {{HMS|Prince George|1772|6}}, followed by {{HMS|Barfleur|1768|6}} and then {{HMS|Christian VII|1807|6}}, an 80-gun former Danish ship captured at the [[Battle of Copenhagen (1807)|Battle of Copenhagen]] in 1807.<ref name="United Service"/>

==Knighthood and flag rank==
Yorke was knighted during this period of service, on 21 April 1805, by [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15809|page=683|date=21 May 1805}}</ref> On 23 April, Yorke was present at the installation of the [[Order of the Garter|Knights of the Garter]], standing in for his brother, [[Philip Yorke, 3rd Earl of Hardwicke|Philip Yorke]], [[Earl of Hardwicke]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15800|page=550|date=23 April 1805}}</ref> Philip was at this time [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]], and so was unable to be present in person.<ref name="United Service"/> In 1810 Joseph Yorke's brother, [[Charles Philip Yorke]] became [[Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]] and Joseph was transferred from command of the ''Christian VII'' to take up a seat on the [[Board of Admiralty]].<ref name="United Service"/>

Joseph Yorke was promoted to [[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)|Rear-Admiral of the Blue]] on 31 July 1810 and hoisted his flag in the 74-gun {{HMS|Vengeance|1774|6}} in January 1811.<ref name="United Service"/> He sailed to the [[Tagus]] carrying reinforcements for [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Arthur Wellesley's]] army, fighting in the [[Peninsular War]].<ref name="United Service"/> After carrying this out he escorted a fleet returning to Britain from the [[East Indies]]. Yorke was promoted to Rear-Admiral of the White on 12 August 1812,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16632|page=1584|date=11 August 1812}}</ref> Rear-Admiral of the Red on 4 December 1813<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16821|page=2432|date=4 December 1813}}</ref> and Vice-Admiral of the Blue on 14 June 1814.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16906|page=1187|date=7 June 1814}}</ref> He served as [[First Sea Lord|First Naval Lord]] in the [[Liverpool ministry]] from October 1813 until May 1816<ref>Rodger, p. 69</ref> but remained on the Admiralty Board until April 1818.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sainty, JC, ''Lord High Admiral and Commissioners of the Admiralty 1660–1870, Office-Holders in Modern Britain: Volume 4: Admiralty Officials 1660–1870'' (1975), pp. 18–31.|url=http://british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=16652| accessdate =4 September 2009}}</ref> He was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the restructuring of that order in January 1815,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16972|page=19|date=4 January 1815}}</ref> promoted Vice-Admiral of the White on 12 August 1819,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=17505|page=1446|date=12 August 1819}}</ref> and promoted to Admiral of the Blue on 22 July 1830.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=18709|page=1539|date=23 July 1830}}</ref>

==Parliamentary career==
Yorke stood as a candidate for the constituency of [[Reigate (UK Parliament constituency)|Reigate]] in 1790, and was returned as its [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|member]].<ref name="United Service"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=13217|page=433|date=10 July 1790}}</ref> He represented the borough<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15497|page=747|date=13 July 1802}}</ref> until 1806, when he was elected as member for [[St Germans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Germans]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15976|page=1506|date=18 November 1806}}</ref> He stood aside, "taking the [[Stewardship of the Chiltern Hundreds|Chiltern Hundreds]]" in 1810 so that his brother, Charles Philip Yorke, could be elected.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16366|page=644|date=1 May 1810}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom general election, 1812|1812 general election]] Joseph Yorke stood as a candidate for [[Sandwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Sandwich]] and was returned as its member.<ref name="United Service"/> He represented the borough until 1818 when he was re-elected to the Reigate constituency, which he represented until his death.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=18719|page=1783|date=20 August 1830}}<br />{{London Gazette|issue=18802|page=901|date=10 May 1831}}</ref> Yorke's business interests include the chairmanship of the Waterloo Bridge Company.<ref name="United Service"/>

==Family and personal life==
On 29 March 1798, Yorke married Elizabeth Weake Rattray, the daughter of James Rattray, in Ireland. The couple had a number of children before Elizabeth's death on 20 January 1812.<ref name="United Service"/> His eldest son, [[Charles Yorke, 4th Earl of Hardwicke|Charles Yorke]] also served in the navy, rising to the rank of admiral, and on the death without heir of Joseph Yorke's brother Philip, the 3rd Earl of Hardwicke in 1834, Charles became the 4th Earl. His daughter Agneta Elizabeth Yorke married the banker [[Robert Cooper Lee Bevan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bevan, Robert Cooper Lee (1809–1890)|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/47420|website=ODNB|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>

On 22 May 1813, Joseph married a second time, to Urania Anne, the [[Earl of Clanricarde|Dowager Marchioness of Clanricarde]], and daughter of [[George Paulet, 12th Marquess of Winchester]], at St. Martin in the Fields, Westminster, London. The marriage did not produce any children.<ref name="United Service"/>

==Death==
On 5 May 1831 Yorke was returning from visiting [[Henry Hotham]]'s [[flagship]], {{HMS|St Vincent|1815|6}}, then moored at [[Spithead]]. He was making his way back to shore aboard the yacht ''Catherine'', in company with Captains Matthew Barton Bradby and Thomas Young, and a seaman named John Chandler, when the boat was struck by lightning in [[Stokes Bay]], causing it to capsize.<ref name="United Service"/><ref>Laughton, ''ODNB''</ref> All aboard were drowned. The bodies were later recovered and an inquest returned a verdict of accidental death.<ref name="United Service"/> Yorke was buried at the family tomb in the parish church at [[Wimpole]], close to [[Wimpole Estate|Wimpole Hall]], the seat of the Earls of Hardwicke.<ref name="United Service"/><ref name="YorkeDeaths">{{cite web|url=http://www.wimpole.info/yorke_deaths.htm#jsy
|title=Melancholy Death of Sir Joseph Yorke 1768–1831 |date=9 May 1831
 |accessdate=2008-09-18|work=|publisher=[[The Times]]}} (Announcement in [[The Times]], p.3, reproduced at www.wimpole.info</ref>

