{{Use British English|date=March 2014}} [[File:St Lawrence Lime.jpg|thumb|upright|The St Lawrence Lime in 2003]] The '''St Lawrence Lime Tree''' was a {{convert|90|ft||adj=mid|-high [[lime tree]]|disp=flip|abbr=out}}<ref name=tele>{{cite web|last=Sapsted |first=David |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1480905/Crickets-famous-lime-tree-stumped-after-200-years.html |title=Cricket's famous lime tree stumped after 200 years |work=Telegraph |date=2005-01-11 |accessdate=2014-03-10}}</ref> at the [[St Lawrence Ground]] in [[Canterbury]], [[Kent]], England. It was located within the boundary ropes of the [[cricket]] pitch which required special rules. In 2005, it was broken in two in high winds.
== History == It is not known when the tree was planted but it is known that it was already full-grown in its location in 1847, when the St Lawrence Ground was opened.<ref name=tele /> The St Lawrence Ground was built around the tree, which was located within the boundary ropes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/4160973.stm |title=End of innings for cricket tree |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-01-10 |accessdate=2014-03-10}}</ref> As a result of the St Lawrence Ground being the only first-class ground with a tree in the playing area, special laws were enacted regarding the tree. These laws may have been instigated pre-1910 where a [[Hampshire County Cricket Club]] batsman was claimed to be caught by a [[Kent County Cricket Club]] fielder off the tree.<ref name=espn>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/218839.html |title=Wisden &ndash; The end of the lime |publisher=ESPN |date= |accessdate=2014-03-10}}</ref> The laws stated that if the ball hit the tree, it was scored as a four even if it would have gone on to score six otherwise and no batsman could be caught out from a rebound off the tree.<ref name=tele /> It was viewed as a challenge to hit a ball over the tree; only four batsmen, [[Arthur Watson (cricketer, born 1884)|Arthur Watson]], [[Learie Constantine]], [[Jim Smith (cricketer)|Jim Smith]] and [[Carl Hooper]], managed to do so.<ref name=tele /><ref>Watson was missed from several reports which named only Constantine, Smith, and Hooper but his place on this list is specifically noted by [[Frank_Keating_(journalist)|Frank Keating]] in the following: Keating F (2005) [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/jan/14/comment.frankkeating Notes from the touchline], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2005-01-14. Retrieved 2016-01-26.</ref>
===Death and replacement=== [[File:Lime tree view (33886298086).jpg|thumb|The replacement St Lawrence Lime in 2017]] In 1999, the St Lawrence Lime was diagnosed with [[Heart rot|heartwood fungus]] and given an expected lifespan of 10 years despite [[pollarding]] aimed to promote growth.<ref name=new /> In preparation, a replacement ''Tilia'' sapling was planted at the St Lawrence Ground by [[E. W. Swanton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/Cricket/Trees-demise-stumps-officials/2005/01/11/1105423488891.html |title=Tree's demise stumps officials |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2005-01-12 |accessdate=2014-03-10}}</ref> Weakened by the fungus, the trunk of the tree was broken in two by high winds on 8 January 2005, leaving a {{convert|7|ft|abbr=on|disp=flip}} stump. Kent initially planned to use the replacement to take the place of the St Lawrence Lime and had permission from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] to do so.<ref name=tele /> However, because the replacement was still small and was deemed unable to take a cricket ball and being less visible to players,<ref name=espn /> it was planted in the playing area outside the boundary ropes instead of inside to take the place of the St Lawrence Lime in a ceremony including [[Chris Cowdrey]].<ref name=new>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/4328651.stm |title=Cricket club reveal new lime tree |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-03-08 |accessdate=2014-03-10}}</ref>
