{{about|Æthelburg of Wessex|the wife of [[Edwin of Northumbria]], who founded the Lyminge monastery in Kent|Æthelburh of Kent}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox royalty | name = Æthelburg | title = | image = | caption = | succession = [[List of Wessex consorts|Queen consort of Wessex]] | reign = c. 688-726 | reign-type = Reign | predecessor = Cynethryth | successor = [[Frithugyth]] | spouse = [[Ine of Wessex]] | consort = | issue = | house = | father = | mother = | birth_date = {{circa|673}} | birth_place = | death_date = c. {{Death year and age|740|673}} | death_place = | burial_date = | burial_place = | religion = }} '''Queen Æthelburg''', (also '''Æthelburh''' or '''Ethelburga''') (ca. 673-740) was Queen of Wessex by marriage to King [[Ine of Wessex]]. Perhaps most famed for her act in 722, when she destroyed the stronghold of [[Taunton]] (which had been built by Ine) in an attempt to find the rebel [[Ealdbert]].<ref> {{cite book|last=Ashley|first=Mike|title=The Mammoth Book of British Kings and Queens|publisher=Robinson Publishing|location=London|year=1998|page=309}}</ref>
==Life==
Æthelburg was born circa 673. She was the wife of King [[Ine of Wessex]]. Æthelburg is considered by some historians to be one of the few Anglo-Saxon women warriors.<ref name="BrineCiletti2010">{{cite book|author1=Kevin R. Brine|author2=Elena Ciletti|author3=Henrike Lähnemann|title=The Sword of Judith: Judith Studies Across the Disciplines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K5eFrFG0Tv4C&pg=PA172|year=2010|publisher=Open Book Publishers|isbn=978-1-906924-15-7|pages=172–}}</ref> In 722, Æthelburg burned down the city of [[Taunton]], a city built by Ine, to avoid its destruction by enemies.<ref name="Ine">{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Ine |volume=14|pages=508–509}}</ref> In 726 King [[Ine of Wessex]] abdicated the throne, and, with Æthelburg, went to [[Rome]].<ref>Parks, George B. 1954. The English traveler to [[Italy]]. First volume, First volume. Roma: Edizioni di storia e letteratura. 31</ref>
==Legacy== Æthelburg of Wessex is sometimes confused with [[Æthelburg of Kent]], the wife of [[Edwin of Northumbria]], who founded the Lyminge monastery in [[Kent]]. Æthelburg is a featured figure on [[Judy Chicago]]'s installation piece ''[[The Dinner Party]]'', being represented as one of the 999 names on the ''[[List of women in the Heritage Floor|Heritage Floor]].
In ''The Dinner Party'' the character Æthelburg is actually a combination of Æthelburg of Wessex and Æthelburg of Kent.<ref name="C105">Chicago, 105.</ref><ref name="Aethel">{{cite web | author= | year=2007 | title=Aethelburg | work=Elizabeth A. Sackler Center for Feminist Art: The Dinner Party: Heritage Floor: Aethelburg | publisher=[[Brooklyn Museum]] | url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/dinner_party/heritage_floor/aethelburg.php | accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>[[Lina Eckenstein|Eckenstein, Lina]], 1963. Woman under [[monasticism]]; chapters on saint-lore and convent life between 500 and 1500. (New York: Russell & Russell), 84.</ref>
